er has served as a powerful metaphor for reinforcing racial hierarchy-and as an even more powerful metaphor for shaping anti-racist critique. Illuminating the power of parody and reappropriation, Black Frankenstein tells the story of a metaphor that continues to matter to literature, culture, aesthetics, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWhite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFrankenstein's monster (Fictitious character). 0aFrankenstein, Victor (Fictitious character)xPolitical aspects. 0aFrankenstein, Victor (Fictitious character). 0aMetaphor in literature. 0aMonsters in literature. 0aMonsters in motion picturesxSchwarze <Motiv>xUSA. 0aMonsters in motion pictures. 0aRace in literature. 0aRace relations in literature. 4aAfrican. 4aAmerican. 4aAmericans. 4aElizabeth. 4aFrankenstein. 4aUS. 4aYoung. 4aappears. 4ablack. 4aboth. 4aculture. 4aessays. 4afiction. 4afigure. 4afilm. 4afrequency. 4aidentifies. 4ainterprets. 4amedia. 4amonster. 4anineteenth-. 4aoratory. 4aother. 4apainting. 4asurprising. 4athroughout. 4atwentieth-century. 4awhites. 4awith. 4aworks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479809608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479809608.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK